'''Ricardo Javier Tavarelli Paiva''' (born [[August 2]], [[1970]] in [[Asunci<U+00F3>n]], [[Paraguay]]) is a former Paraguayan [[Football (soccer)|footballer]], who played as a [[goalkeeper]].

==Career==
Tavarelli started his career in the youth divisions of [[Tacuary]] and then moved to the youth divisions of [[Olimpia Asunci<U+00F3>n|Club Olimpia]], where he made his debut in the first team squad in 1992, playing the [[Torneo Republica]].<ref>[http://www.labarradelao.com.py/info/entrevistamono.html Entrevista a Tavarelli]</ref> In Olimpia he would go on to win several national and international championships, becoming a fan-favorite. Tavarelli was a pivotal part of the 2002 Olimpia team that won the [[Copa Libertadores]]. His skills helped Olimpia win two key penalty shoot-outs against [[Gr<U+00EA>mio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr<U+00EA>mio]] of Porto Alegre (semi-finals) and [[Sao Caetano]] (finals). In 2004 he played for [[Gr<U+00EA>mio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr<U+00EA>mio]] of [[Brazil]] with little success. Tavarelli returned to [[Olimpia Asunci<U+00F3>n|Club Olimpia]] and also had a brief sting playing for [[Sportivo Luque<U+00F1>o]] before finally retiring. He earned the nickname "Mono" ([[monkey]]) because of his quick goalkeeping skills.

Tavarelli was also part of the [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguayan national team]] in the Korea / Japan [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>[http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=178244/index.html FIFA Profile]</ref> 

Tavarelli's sister, Giselle, is the wife of Paraguayan footballer [[Roque Santa Cruz]].

